The Debt Management Office (DMO) on behalf of the federal government is set to raise N60 billion from through reopening of three FGN Bonds next week having raised N50 billion from the bond auction held last month. This is coming two weeks after it announced the suspension of the FGN Savings Bond Offer for the month of April due to the effects of the COVID-19 pandemic as it assures that the suspension of the April 2020 offer will not affect coupon payments due to investors for already issued FGN securities. The debt office in the bond auction notice released yesterday said it plans to raise N20 billion each from the 12.75% FGN APR 2023 5-year paper, 12.5% FGN MAR 2035 15-year paper and 12.98 % FGN APR 2050 30-year paper at the auction scheduled for next week Wednesday,  April 22, 2020. Last month, the DMO had raked in N50 billion from auction from the tree bond in addition to N20 billion realised from non competitive bids from two of the bonds. The March 2020 bond auction was not disappointing as it met the N50 billion expectation, although the short term bond did underperform. As against the N15 billion it planned to raise from the 5-year paper, the debt office had realised only N5 billion from the seven successful bids which had been at 10 per cent marginal rate. Investors also put in N10 billion in the bond through the non competitive bids. For the 15- and 30-year bonds the DMO had allotted N20 billion and N25 billion in spite of the N69.01 billion and N91.8 billion subscription offered for the two bonds respectively. Last month, the DMO whilst noting that arrangements have been made to ensure that all coupon payments for and redemption of FGN securities are made as and when due to investors’ designated accounts, said the suspension of the bond auction which had earlier been scheduled for the second week of April was due to the lockdown order by the presidency. “His Excellency, President Muhammadu Buhari, during a nation-wide broadcast on the coronavirus (COVID-19) yesterday (Sunday) announced restrictions of movement in the Federal Capital Territory (FCT), Lagos and Ogun States. The restriction of movement was based on the need to keep the populace safe and contain the spread of the disease. “As a result of this development, the Debt Management Office (DMO) wishes to inform the general public that the FGN Savings Bond Offer for the month of April 2020, which was scheduled for April 6 – 10, 2020 has been suspended,” the DMO had said in a statement. 